content.text: Good, I can see the `frpm` table has `Enrollment (K-12)` and `Free Meal Count (K-12)` columns. Now let me find the 10th and 11th highest-enrollment K-12 schools and their eligible free rates.

input.command:
sqlite3 "/Users/david/workspace/claimdb/test_dbs/california_schools.sqlite" "
SELECT 
  \"School Name\",
  \"Enrollment (K-12)\",
  \"Free Meal Count (K-12)\",
  CASE WHEN \"Enrollment (K-12)\" > 0 
    THEN \"Free Meal Count (K-12)\" * 1.0 / \"Enrollment (K-12)\" 
    ELSE NULL END AS eligible_free_rate
FROM frpm
WHERE \"Enrollment (K-12)\" IS NOT NULL
ORDER BY \"Enrollment (K-12)\" DESC
LIMIT 15;
"
input.description: Find top 15 schools by K-12 enrollment with free meal rates

content.text:
Now let me identify the 10th and 11th highest-enrollment schools clearly:

- **Rank 10**: El Camino Real Charter High — Enrollment: 3868, Free Rate: ~13.4%
- **Rank 11**: Eleanor Roosevelt High — Enrollment: 3868, Free Rate: ~29.1%

Wait, ranks 10 and 11 have the same enrollment (3868). Let me check if there's a tie-breaking consideration, and also verify the rates against 35%.

input.command:
sqlite3 "/Users/david/workspace/claimdb/test_dbs/california_schools.sqlite" "
SELECT 
  ROW_NUMBER() OVER (ORDER BY \"Enrollment (K-12)\" DESC) as rank,
  \"School Name\",
  \"Enrollment (K-12)\",
  \"Free Meal Count (K-12)\",
  ROUND(\"Free Meal Count (K-12)\" * 100.0 / \"Enrollment (K-12)\", 2) AS pct_free
FROM frpm
WHERE \"Enrollment (K-12)\" IS NOT NULL AND \"Enrollment (K-12)\" > 0
ORDER BY \"Enrollment (K-12)\" DESC
LIMIT 15;
"
